          "content": "The issue is clear now. In `protocol.go`'s `Dial`, the order is:\n\n1. `ConnectWithCb(cfg, host, port, ud)` → calls `nxp_connect_go` which sets callbacks on the connection\n2. `conn.SetStreamAcceptCb(ud)` → calls `nxp_conn_set_stream_accept_go`\n\nBut look at `nxp_connect_go` in `nxp.go`:\n\n```c\nstatic nxp_result nxp_connect_go(const nxp_config *cfg, const char *host,\n                                  uint16_t port, void *ud, nxp_conn **out) {\n    return nxp_connect(cfg, host, port, goOnConnected, goOnClosed, ud, out);\n}\n```\n\nThis passes `goOnConnected`/`goOnClosed` to `nxp_connect` which stores them in `ac->on_connected`/`ac->on_closed`. That's correct.\n\nBut then `SetCallbacks` in `goOnNewConn` (server side) calls `nxp_conn_set_callbacks(conn, goOnConnected, goOnClosed, ud)` on the **server-accepted conn**. That should work too.\n\nThe real problem: **thread safety**. The C event loop is **single-threaded by design** (the comment says \"Single-threaded model\"). The Go code calls `nxp_connect` from the main goroutine while `nxp_poll` is running concurrently in a separate goroutine. This is a data race on `g_nxp`.\n\nThe fix is to call all NXP API functions from a **single goroutine** — the same one that drives `nxp_poll`. I need to serialize all C calls through one goroutine.",
