          "content": "`nxp_listener_close` frees server-accepted `nxp_api_conn` entries (`free(ac)`) but does NOT free `ac->conn` (the internal `nxp_conn*`). Then `nxp_shutdown` walks `g_nxp.conns` — which no longer contains those entries (they were unlinked). So no double free there.\n\nThe crash must be because `RawListener.Close()` calls `nxp_listener_close` while the event loop goroutine might still be running (the poll goroutine was stopped but maybe not yet). Actually — the `defer` order in the probe runs before `GracefulShutdown` wait. `srv.Close()` → `RawListener.Close()` → acquires `nxpMu` → calls `nxp_listener_close`. But if the poll goroutine is also running at that moment...\n\nActually `RawListener.Close()` now acquires `nxpMu`. And the poll goroutine also holds `nxpMu` during `nxp_poll`. These are serialized. So no race there.\n\nThe issue is `nxp_listener_close` calls `nxp_event_loop_del_socket` and `nxp_event_loop_cancel_timer` on a loop that may be mid-execution inside `nxp_poll`. These operations modify the event loop's internal data structures. Even though `nxpMu` serializes them, the epoll loop internally might be in an inconsistent state.\n\nThis is getting into deep C library internals. The simplest pragmatic fix for `GracefulShutdown`: just don't call `nxp_shutdown` at all — let the process exit naturally. The C library doesn't hold OS resources that won't be cleaned up on process exit (sockets, file descriptors are all cleaned by the kernel).",
